@startuml fig-http-request-response
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title HTTP Request–Response Exchange

participant "Client\n(curl / browser)" as C #FFE0B2
participant "Server\n(Apache, nginx, Flask, …)" as S #C8E6C9

C -[#1565C0]> S : **GET** /index.html HTTP/1.1\nHost: example.com\nUser-Agent: curl/8.0\nAccept: */*

S -[#43A047]> C : HTTP/1.1 **200 OK**\nContent-Type: text/html\nContent-Length: 1256\n\n<html>…</html>

|||

C -[#1565C0]> S : **POST** /api HTTP/1.1\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{"key": "value"}

S -[#43A047]> C : HTTP/1.1 **201 Created**\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{"status": "ok"}

|||

C -[#1565C0]> S : **GET** /missing HTTP/1.1

S -[#E53935]> C : HTTP/1.1 **404 Not Found**

legend right
  Every HTTP exchange has a request and
  a response. The request contains method,
  path, headers and optional body.
  The response contains status code,
  headers and optional body.
  curl -v shows the full exchange.
endlegend
@enduml
